      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im working on this RBAC system for our new SaaS module and the permission logic is getting super messy. i need a function `check_permission(user, resource, action)` that follows our hierarchy.\n\nhere is the setup:\n- roles: 'admin' > 'editor' > 'viewer'\n- admin can do anything on any resource.\n- editor can 'read' and 'write' if they own the resource or if the resource is 'public'.\n- viewer can only 'read' if the resource is 'public'.\n\ni need this to pass these specific checks for our current staging users:\n\n```python\nclass User:\n    def __init__(self, id, role):\n        self.id = id\n        self.role = role\n\nclass Resource:\n    def __init__(self, id, owner_id, is_public):\n        self.id = id\n        self.owner_id = owner_id\n        self.is_public = is_public\n\n# Test cases\nu1 = User(id=101, role='admin')\nu2 = User(id=202, role='editor')\nu3 = User(id=303, role='viewer')\n\nr1 = Resource(id=1, owner_id=202, is_public=False)\nr2 = Resource(id=2, owner_id=999, is_public=True)\n\n# All these MUST return True\nassert check_permission(u1, r1, 'delete') == True\nassert check_permission(u2, r1, 'write') == True\nassert check_permission(u3, r2, 'read') == True\n\n# All these MUST return False\nassert check_permission(u2, r2, 'delete') == False\nassert check_permission(u3, r1, 'read') == False\nassert check_permission(u2, r2, 'write') == False # Wait, u2 is editor, r2 is public... actually u2 should be able to write to public. \n# My bad, fix the logic to match: editor can write if public.\n# Let's re-run:\nassert check_permission(u2, r2, 'write') == True \n# and viewer can't write\nassert check_permission(u3, r2, 'write') == False\n\nprint(\"all tests passed!\")\n```\ncan u write the function for me? i just need it to pass these assertions so i can push to staging.",
